        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD’s note has not been found. Müller had expressed his wish to see an article by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_389.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred William Bennett</ref> on <hi rend="italic">Viola tricolor</hi> (Bennett 1873; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8907.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hermann Müller, 19 May 1873</ref> and n. 4). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3286.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Meehan</ref> had discussed the fertilisation of asparagus at a meeting of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia (see Meehan 1872b). <hi rend="italic">Plusia</hi> is a genus of moths. <hi rend="italic">Glyceria fluitans</hi> is a species of aquatic perennial grasses; <hi rend="italic">Mythimna pudorina</hi> (the striped wainscot moth) feeds on both its pollen and its nectar (Heath <hi rend="italic">et al.</hi> 1979–, 9: 262; see also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8912F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Friedrich Hildebrand, 15 May 1873</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4503.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Christian Konrad Sprengel’s</ref> discussion of the secretion of nectar in <hi rend="italic">Secale cereale</hi> (rye) is in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7390.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sprengel 1793</ref>, pp. 79–80. In his copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7390.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sprengel 1793</ref>, p. 79 (Darwin Library–CUL), CD noted that Sprengel confessed in his introduction that he knew ‘no use for nectar in grasses’ (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 780).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Poa annua</hi> is annual meadow-grass.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Müller refers to Bennett 1873 (see n. 1, above). Sprengel coined the term dichogamy to describe the condition in which male and female sex organs of a hermaphroditic flower mature at different times (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7390.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sprengel 1793</ref>, pp. 17–19).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See Meehan 1872b, p. 139.</note>
        </div>        
            
